sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: tetR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Coding region for the TetR protein without the Ribosome Binding Site. Modified with an LVA tail for rapid degradation of the protein and faster fall time for the emission. TetR binds to the pTet regulator (BBa_R0040). aTc (anhydrotetracycline) binds to TetR and inhibits its operation.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
References (unparsed) here:

Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999).

Lutz R, Bujard H., Independent and tight regulation of transcriptional units in Escherichia coli via the LacR/O, the TetR/O and AraC/I1-I2 regulatory elements. Nucleic Acids Res. 1997 Mar 15;25(6):1203-10. PMID: 9092630

References (unparsed) here:

Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999).

Lutz R, Bujard H., Independent and tight regulation of transcriptional units in Escherichia coli via the LacR/O, the TetR/O and AraC/I1-I2 regulatory elements. Nucleic Acids Res. 1997 Mar 15;25(6):1203-10. PMID: 9092630

BBa_C0040 TetR Protein is based on the TetR sequence from Elowitz's repressilator. It has been modified to include a rapid degradation LVA tail, and includes the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites. The RBS has been removed. The stop codon has been changed from TAA to a double stop codon TAATAA.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K137047
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Primers were synthesized to bind to part Q04400, and then a PCR reaction was run.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Inverted tetR promoter with noncoding, spacer DNA downstream of it to make the total length 250 bp. The promoter faces the 5' direction.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This part is in a series of inverted tetR promoters that have total lengths of 150, 250, 350, 450, 650, and 850 bp. We chose the region upstream of tetR in part Q04400 to be the noncoding DNA segment. This noncoding segment consists of the 3' end of tetR and B0015. None of the parts in this series was long enough to include the start codon of tetR, so a functional tetR protein should not be transcribed.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Allen Lin

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: Bxb1_Int
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Mycobacterium Phage Bxb1 gp35, DNA integrase
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part is derived by Mycobacterium phage Bxb1. And synthesized by Bioneer. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/NP_075302.1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part is the protein coding sequence which encodes DNA integrase of Mycobacterium phage Bxb1. The Bxb1 integrase is a DNA recombinase, more precisely a member of serine integrase family. It recognizes specific sequences, called attB and attP, and then integrate, invert, or excise depend on orientations of recognition sequences. We used this integrase to invert specific sequence contained in plasmid. This protein is well expressed in E.coli(strain MG1655). When it inverts DNA, the attB and attP sequences are changed into attL and attR, as common DNA recombinases do. Another protein called Bxb1 excisionase interacts with integrase and that complex flips back inverted DNA into original sequence regenerating attB and attP sequences.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Internal restriction endonuclease site is changed(two PstI sites, one XbaI sites) without changing amino acid sequence.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Dong-hui Choe, Soo-in Lee

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: pBAD
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The sequence was obtained by applying all mutations that upregulated AraC binding and subsequent promoter activity listed in reference [1].
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: pBAD is an E.coli promoter that is induced by L-arabinose. K206000 is a mutagenized pBAD promoter that is responsive to lower concentrations of arabinose than wild type (I13453) and, additionally, exhibits a higher maximum of protein expression as measured by coupling to a fluorescent reporter.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: There were no special design considerations.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Amelia Hardjasa

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
